{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 18:03:33.219452", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Diagnostic report — Clos (fat-tree) EBGP lab\\nDate: now\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Control plane (FRR BGP) across the fabric is broadly healthy: EBGP sessions between leaves, spines and the super-spine are established and routes are being exchanged (multiple peers Up, prefixes learned).\\n- Data-plane between working host and fabric is OK: ping tests completed successfully between host pc_0_1 and the opposite leaf (10.0.0.1) and from a leaf router to pc_0_1.\\n- Primary anomaly: pc_0_0 appears to be down (container not running). Evidence in tooling shows the host container could not be queried and the leaf interface facing that host shows zero traffic.\\n- No router BGP sessions are in Idle/Active or otherwise down; no obvious route blackholes or dropped BGP sessions were observed from the collected outputs.\\n\\nObserved anomalies (high level)\\n1. Host pc_0_0 is not accessible by the management tool (container not running).\\n   - Tool error: when attempting to collect pc_0_0 network info: \"container ... is not running\".\\n   - The leaf attached to that host (leaf_router_0_0) shows the host-facing interface with 10.0.0.1 and zero RX/TX on that interface (no host traffic observed).\\n   - This is the only clear abnormality in the data collected.\\n\\n2. Minor observational inconsistencies in per-interface counters reported by ifconfig vs. ping results for other host (likely sampling/timing), but nothing that indicates loss of connectivity or persistent forwarding problems across routers.\\n\\nDetailed findings and evidence\\n\\nA. Hosts\\n- pc_0_0\\n  - get_host_net_config failed: \"container ... is not running\" (tool error). No ifconfig/ip output available.\\n  - Inference: pc_0_0 VM/container is stopped and therefore not participating in the network.\\n\\n- pc_0_1\\n  - ifconfig / ip: eth0 = 10.0.1.2/24\\n  - Route: default via 10.0.1.1\\n  - Ping tests:\\n    - From leaf_router_0_1 to 10.0.1.2: 4/4 replies, avg RTT 1.08 ms.\\n    - From pc_0_1 to 10.0.0.1: 4/4 replies, avg RTT 2.34 ms.\\n  - Conclusion: pc_0_1 is up and traffic to/from it works.\\n\\nB. Leaf routers\\n- leaf_router_0_0 (host-facing: eth8 = 10.0.0.1/24)\\n  - ifconfig shows eth8 10.0.0.1 with RX packets 0 TX packets 0.\\n  - Routing table contains many 10.x.0.0/24 networks learned via EBGP (via 172.16.1.0 dev eth0).\\n  - BGP (vtysh show ip bgp summary):\\n    - BGP router ID 172.16.1.1, local AS 65200.\\n    - 8 EBGP neighbors (spine interfaces) — all peers appear Up (Up/Down shows ~00:03:02) and each peer has PfxRcd = 31; total peers = 8.\\n  - Interpretation: leaf_router_0_0 has BGP adjacency up with its spines and has the expected routing information, but its host-facing interface shows no host traffic — consistent with host down.\\n\\n- leaf_router_0_1 (host-facing: eth8 = 10.0.1.1/24)\\n  - ifconfig shows eth8 10.0.1.1/24.\\n  - BGP summary:\\n    - BGP router ID 172.16.1.3, local AS 65201.\\n    - 8 EBGP neighbors — all peers Up and PfxRcd = 31.\\n  - Ping from leaf_router_0_1 -> pc_0_1 succeeded (1.08 ms avg).\\n  - Interpretation: leaf_router_0_1 is healthy and forwarding to its host.\\n\\nC. Spine routers\\n- spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1\\n  - Both have multiple EBGP neighbors (to super-spine and to leaves). BGP summaries show peers Up and prefixes being exchanged.\\n  - Example from spine_router_0_0:\\n    - local AS 65100, peers to super-spine (AS 65000) are Up; peers to leaves (AS 652xx) show PfxRcd = 1 (each leaf advertises its /24).\\n  - show ip bgp neighbors / routes indicate they have multi-path next-hops for various 10.x.0.0/24 networks — the spine plane has full view of routes.\\n\\nD. Super-spine (super_spine_router_0)\\n- Local AS 65000; many EBGP neighbors (spines) — BGP table populated.\\n- show ip bgp 10.0.0.0/24 shows multiple external paths from different spine routers; best path chosen (via 172.16.0.1, AS path 65100 65200).\\n- Super-spine shows many 10.x.0.0/24 networks reachable via spines; BGP replication appears correct.\\n\\nRouting / BGP health summary (evidence)\\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP summary lists 8 neighbors with PfxRcd = 31 each (neighbors: 172.16.1.0, .16, .32, .48, .64, .80, .96, .112).\\n- leaf_router_0_1 BGP summary similarly healthy.\\n- spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 BGP summaries show multi-hop next-hops for the 10.x.0.0/24 prefixes and all EBGP neighbors Up.\\n- super_spine_router_0 show ip bgp 10.0.0.0/24 shows 8 available external paths and a selected best path — consistent with expected EBGP fabric behavior.\\n\\nReachability tests performed\\n- leaf_router_0_1 -> 10.0.1.2 (pc_0_1): 4/4 success, avg 1.078 ms.\\n- pc_0_1 -> 10.0.0.1 (leaf_router_0_0): 4/4 success, avg 2.342 ms.\\n  - These show inter-pod connectivity and that the fabric forwards host-to-host and host-to-leaf traffic correctly when both hosts are present/operational.\\n- Attempt to query pc_0_0 failed at collection step (container not running) — no pings attempted to that host because the orchestration layer reports it stopped.\\n\\nLocalization of fault(s)\\n- Fault localized to host pc_0_0 (the workload/container for that host is not running). Evidence:\\n  - Tool error when fetching pc_0_0 config: \"container ... is not running\".\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 host-facing interface (10.0.0.1) shows zero RX/TX counters — no traffic observed to/from a host on that subnet.\\n- No router or BGP adjacency failures detected in the collected router outputs; no other host reported unreachable.\\n\\nRoot cause analysis (summary)\\n- Direct root cause for the only anomaly: host-container/service-level failure for pc_0_0. The container is not running (as reported by the collection tool), resulting in the host being absent from the network (no L2/L3 traffic on leaf_router_0_0:eth8).\\n- No evidence that the network forwarding plane or BGP control plane caused this host outage. Router interfaces and EBGP sessions are Up and routes propagate correctly; the fabric appears operational.\\n\\nOther notes / observations\\n- Some interface counters reported as zero for host-facing interfaces while pings succeeded for different host — this may be due to timing between snapshot collection and tests or minor sampling differences. It does not indicate systemic packet forwarding failure given the successful pings and intact BGP state.\\n- BGP prefix counts and next-hop multipath information appear consistent with an EBGP Clos design where leaves advertise host /24s and spines/super-spine aggregate/propagate those routes.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Network control plane (BGP) and inter-router connectivity: healthy.\\n- Data plane between active hosts and fabric: healthy (confirmed by pings).\\n- Only identified abnormality is a host-level outage: pc_0_0 (container not running), localized to that host and its leaf (leaf_router_0_0 shows no host traffic). This explains any unreachability of that host’s IP/prefix; fabric and routing appear to be functioning correctly otherwise.\\n\\nIf you want, I can next:\\n- attempt targeted router/host commands to further validate (e.g., restart or query pc_0_0 if you want remediation), or\\n- collect historical counters/logs (BGP logs, interface counters over time) for deeper forensics. (Do not perform any of these unless you request them.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='bee26ca0-76da-41af-a86b-44b3f6b81fad'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
